---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const playgroundExample = `.feature-panel {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-m);
}

.feature-panel > .title {
    margin: 0;
}

.feature-panel--highlighted {
    border-color: var(--colour-accent);
}`;

const stateExample = `.feature-panel.is_active {
    border-color: var(--colour-accent);
}`;

const brokenExample = `.page .wrapper .feature-panel .title {
    color: red !important;
}`;

const fixedExample = `@layer components, theme;

@layer theme {
    .feature-panel > .title {
        color: var(--colour-accent);
    }
}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Playground"
    description="Experimenting with Layered Semantic CSS patterns."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Playground</p>

        <h1>
            Playground
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            A lab for testing component structure, naming, modifiers, state,
            scope, and layering without dragging production code into the fire.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Playground sections">
        <a href="#start">Start here</a>
        <a href="#component">Component experiment</a>
        <a href="#break">Break it</a>
        <a href="#debug">Debug it</a>
        <a href="#next">Next demos</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="start" class="content-block">
        <h2>Start experimenting</h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/playground/live-editor/">Live CSS editor</a></h3>
                <p>Edit CSS directly and test decisions against a real component.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/tools/specificity-calculator/">Specificity calculator</a></h3>
                <p>Check selector weight before you create an override crime scene.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/tools/scope-demo/">Scope demo</a></h3>
                <p>Compare native @scope with traditional shallow component selectors.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="component" class="content-block">
        <h2>Basic component experiment</h2>

        <p>
            Start with one semantic parent component, short child classes, and
            one deliberate modifier. If it needs five utilities and three nested
            wrappers, the component is already filing a complaint.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={playgroundExample} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>State experiment</h2>

        <p>
            Use state classes for temporary UI behaviour. Do not turn loading,
            disabled, or active states into permanent modifiers.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={stateExample} />
    </section>

    <section id="break" class="content-block">
        <h2>Break it on purpose</h2>

        <p>
            Learning is faster when you deliberately create bad CSS and then
            fix it.
        </p>

        <ol>
            <li>Add one extra level of selector nesting.</li>
            <li>Add a modifier for something that is temporary state.</li>
            <li>Add a utility class that duplicates component CSS.</li>
            <li>Move a theme override into the wrong layer.</li>
            <li>Replace a token with a random hard-coded value.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="debug" class="content-block">
        <h2>Debugging flow</h2>

        <p>Bad version:</p>
        <CodeExample code={brokenExample} />

        <p>Better version:</p>
        <CodeExample code={fixedExample} />

        <ol>
            <li>Check layer order before touching specificity.</li>
            <li>Check whether the selector is deeper than it needs to be.</li>
            <li>Check whether state and modifier meaning are mixed together.</li>
            <li>Check whether the value should be a token instead.</li>
            <li>Only then decide whether the code needs a real refactor.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="next" class="content-block">
        <h2>Useful next demos</h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/tools/container-query-visualiser/">Container query visualiser</a></h3>
                <p>Test component responsiveness without viewport guesswork.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/tools/devtools-inspector/">DevTools-style inspector</a></h3>
                <p>Inspect how layers, selectors, and overrides work together.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></h3>
                <p>Use practical rules when a CSS choice stops being obvious.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
